  <entry>
    <id>https://www.nber.org/papers/w34186</id>
    <title>Union Bargaining Power and the Amenity-Wage Tradeoff</title>
    <updated>2025-09-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Lorenzo Lagos</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt; NBER Working Papers&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;This paper studies how collective bargaining affects both wages and amenities. By merging collective bargaining agreements (CBAs) to linked employer-employee data in Brazil, I combine rich contracted amenities with wage information. I implement a difference-in-difference strategy that exploits a court ruling enforcing CBA continuation (i.e., ultractivity) to estimate the effects of union bargaining power. Strengthening unions raises wages and amenities without reducing employment—increasing retention despite some labor-labor substitution. A revealed preference approach shows that amenities account for 45% of total compensation gains. These findings suggest that collective bargaining can offset monopsony power, but employers retain the right-to-manage workforce composition.</content>
    <link href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w34186"/>
    <category term="NBER"/>
    <published>2025-09-01T00:00:00+00:00</published>
